<h3>Design community</h3>

<p>When I joined Defra in 2016 there were 4 designers working in Warrington and Bristol offices. There were no community activities or on-boarding processes for the team.</p>
<p>One of the first things I wanted to do was create a consistent onboarding process giving people access to all the information they might need in one place.
</p>
<p>I created a <a href="https://trello.com/b/HWWDXWv7/permanent-designer-onboarding" class="anchor" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Designer onboarding">Trello board</a> adapted from <a href="https://inclusivedesignrecruitment.co.uk/" class="anchor" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="inclusive recruitment website">Snooks inclusive recruitment website</a></p>

<p>I also set up community events to make sure designers in all offices felt like part of one team. I was able to:
</p>

<ul class="unordered-list">
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Introduce regular cross Defra community meetings, held each month we used this time to learn more about Defra worked as an organisation and had guest speakers from inside and outside of Government
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Set up weekly drop-in sessions, these had no agenda and were an opportunity for people to meet other designers, get quick feedback or ask questions
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Used slack for daily team updates or stand up's to increase awareness, knowledge sharing, and team spirit
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Introduced Design team days for our hubs in Warrington Bristol and York, these helped people to get back into the office and meet other designers face to face
</li>
  <li class="unordered-list__list-item">Set up tailored training with Snook for the design team based on each team member's career conversations and skills gaps/interests.
</li>
  </ul>

